'''M-10''' is a [[Michigan State Trunkline Highway System|state trunkline highway]] in the [[Metro Detroit]] area of Michigan in the United States. The southernmost portion follows [[Jefferson Avenue (Detroit)|Jefferson Avenue]] in downtown [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]], and the southern terminus is at the intersection of Jefferson and [[M-3 (Michigan highway)|M-3]] (Randolph Street) next to the entrance to the [[Detroit<U+2013>Windsor Tunnel]]. The northern terminus is in [[West Bloomfield Township, Michigan|West Bloomfield Township]] at the intersection with Orchard Lake Road. The highway has several names as it runs through residential and commercial areas of the west side of Detroit and into the suburb of [[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]]. It is called the  '''John C. Lodge Freeway''', '''The Lodge''', '''James Couzens Highway''' and '''Northwestern Highway'''.

M-10 was built in segments through the late 1950s and early 1960s. It carried several different names before the entire route was finally officially named the John C. Lodge Freeway in 1987. The [[freeway]] has carried a few other highway designations. The southern segment was part of [[U.S. Route 12 in Michigan|US Highway&nbsp;12]] (US&nbsp;12) and the whole thing was later renumbered [[Interstate 696 Business (Detroit, Michigan)|Business Spur Interstate 696]] (BS I-696). From 1970 until 1986, it was part of [[U.S. Route 10 in Michigan|US&nbsp;10]], and the freeway has been M-10 since. The non-freeway segment that runs between [[Interstate 696|I-696]] in Southfield and Orchard Lake Road was previously numbered '''M-4'''.  M-10 was named after [[John C. Lodge]], an influential Detroiter and [[Mayor of Detroit]] from 1927<U+2013>28.

==Route description==
Running about {{convert|22.8|mi|km}} in the [[Metro Detroit]] area, M-10 runs roughly northwest<U+2013>southeast from [[Downtown Detroit]] into the northern suburbs in [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland County]].<ref name=MDOT14D/> The entire length of the highway is listed as a part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]],<ref name=NHS-DUAMI>{{cite map |author= Michigan Department of Transportation |title= National Highway System: Detroit Urbanized Area |year= 2005 |scale= Scale not given |location= Lansing |publisher= Michigan Department of Transportation |url= http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Detroit_150611_7.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=October 7, 2008}}</ref> a system of roads importance to the nation's economy, defense and mobility.<ref name=NHS>{{cite web |first1= Stefan |last1= Natzke |first2= Mike |last2= Neathery |first3= Kevin |last3= Adderly |url= http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/ |title= What is the National Highway System?  |work= National Highway System  |accessdate= December 12, 2010 |date= August 26, 2010 |publisher= [[Federal Highway Administration]] |last-author-amp=y}}</ref> As a [[Michigan State Trunkline Highway System|state trunkline highway]], the roadway is maintained by the [[Michigan Department of Transportation]] (MDOT), and it includes approximately {{convert|18.5|mi|km}} of freeway.<ref name=PRFA/> M-10 has six lanes from Detroit to Inkster Road in [[Farmington Hills, Michigan|Farmington Hills]], where it drops to four; a few segments have eight lanes for short distances between interchanges.<ref name=google/> According to the department, 28,964&nbsp;vehicles use US&nbsp;127 [[average annual daily traffic|on average]] near on [[Jefferson Avenue (Detroit)|Jefferson Avenue]] in Detroit, and 139,800&nbsp;vehicles do so between [[U.S. Route 24 in Michigan|US&nbsp;24]] (Telegraph Road) and Lahser Road in [[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]], the lowest and highest traffic counts along the highway in 2013, respectively.<ref name=TMIS>{{cite web |author= Bureau of Transportation Planning |url= http://mdotnetpublic.state.mi.us/tmispublic/ |title= Traffic Monitoring Information System |publisher= Michigan Department of Transportation |year= 2008 |accessdate= April 16, 2015}}</ref>

===Detroit===
[[File:CoboHallDetroit.jpg|thumb|left|M-10 passing under Cobo Center]]
M-10 starts at the corner of Jefferson Avenue and Randolph Street in [[Downtown Detroit]], an intersection that also marks the southern end of [[M-3 (Michigan highway)|M-3]] and the western end of [[Interstate 375 Business (Detroit, Michigan)|Business Spur I-375]]. This intersection is also the access to the [[Detroit<U+2013>Windsor Tunnel]] between the [[Renaissance Center]] and the Old [[Mariners' Church]]. From here, M-10 runs west-southwesterly parallel to the [[Detroit River]]  on Jefferson Avenue past [[Hart Plaza]]. At the intersection with [[Woodward Avenue]], M-10 transitions onto the John C. Lodge Freeway, which runs under [[Cobo Center]], home of the [[North American International Auto Show]] each January. The [[freeway]] turns north-northwesterly and away from the Detroit River next to [[Joe Louis Arena]]. North of the Cobo Center curve, M-10 forms the boundary between Downtown Detroit to the east and the [[Corktown, Detroit|Corktown]] neighborhood to the west. The freeway has a pair of [[service drive]]s as it leaves the commercial areas near the [[MGM Grand Detroit]] and the interchange with [[Interstate 75 in Michigan|I-75]] (Fisher Freeway).<ref name=MDOT14D>{{cite MDOT map |year= 2014 |inset= Detroit |sections= C8<U+2013>F11}}</ref><ref name=google>{{google maps |url= https://www.google.com/maps/dir/42.3298267,-83.0422575/42.5297259,-83.3598767/@42.4297504,-83.2069909,60413m/data=!3m1!1e3 |title= Overview Map of M-10 |access-date= April 10, 2015}}</ref>

North of I-75, M-10 forms the border between [[North Corktown, Detroit|North Corktown]] (west) and [[Midtown Detroit]] (east). The freeway passes the [[MotorCity Casino]] at at the interchange with [[Grand River Avenue]]. The rest of its route in the part of the city passes through residential zones. Near the interchange with [[Interstate 94 in Michigan|I-94]] (Edsel Ford Freeway), M-10 passes the campus of [[Wayne State University]]. North of I-94, the Lodge Freeway is the border between the West Side and [[New Center, Detroit|New Center]] . This area is residential on either side of the freeway north of the campus of the [[Henry Ford Hospital]]. North of Clairmont Avenue, M-10 curves to the northwest before resuming its north-northwesterly course near Chicago Boulevard. North of Webb Avenue, the freeway follows the western city limits of [[Highland Park, Michigan|Highland Park]], an [[enclave]] within the city of Detroit. M-10 intersects [[M-8 (Michigan highway)|M-8]] where it transitions between Davison Avenue and the Davison Freeway on the western edge of Highland Park before the Lodge Freeway curves around to run due west.<ref name=MDOT14D/><ref name=google/>

M-10 runs for about {{convert|2|mi|km|spell=in}} on this due westward course before it intersects Wyoming Avenue and turns northwest. The frontage roads change names from John C. Lodge Service Drive to James Couzens Freeway at the Wyoming Avenue interchange. The freeway continues for another {{convert|3+1/2|mi|km}} with interchanges for local streets in this part of Detroit, including 7&nbsp;Mile Road. At the interchange with [[M-102 (Michigan highway)|M-102]] (8&nbsp;Mile Road), the freeway crosses out of Detroit and Wayne County into [[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]] in [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland County]].<ref name=MDOT14D/><ref name=google/>

===Oakland County===
[[File:SouthfieldMichiganSkyline1.jpg|thumb|right|Looking southbound]]
The service drives change names again to Northwestern Highway upon crossing into Oakland County. The east side of M-10 is flanked by the Northland Shopping Center and a campus of [[Oakland Community College]]; the west side is residential. About {{convert|1+1/4|mi|km}} into Southfield, M-10 intersects the northern end of [[M-39 (Michigan highway)|M-39]] (Southfield Freeway) and 9&nbsp;Mile Road. The adjacent properties are mostly residential, but there are some commercial areas centered around the various [[Mile Road System (Detroit)|Mile Roads]], such as the campus of [[Lawrence Technological University]] at 10&nbsp;Mile Road.<ref name=MDOT14D/><ref name=google/> Near Lahser and 11&nbsp;Mile roads, M-10 meets [[Interstate 696|I-696]] (Reuther Freeway) and [[U.S. Route 24 in Michigan|US&nbsp;24]] (Telegraph Road) in a complex interchange called the Mixing Bowl.<ref name=MITA>{{cite news |author= Staff |date= Summer 2007 |title= MITA Presents Michigan Construction Quality Partnership Awards |url= http://www.mi-ita.com/Portals/0/pdf%20files/CQP_Article.pdf |format= PDF |work= Cross-Section |publisher= Michigan Infrastructure and Transportation Association |page= 11 |accessdate= August 30, 2012}}</ref> This interchange is spans over {{convert|2|mi|km|spell=in}} near the [[American Center]]. The [[carriageway]]s for I-696 run in the median of M-10 while partial interchanges connect to Lahser and Franklin roads on either end of the various ramps that connect to I-696 and US&nbsp;24.<ref name=MDOT14D/><ref name=google/>

Northwest of this interchange, M-10 transitions to a [[boulevard]] with [[Michigan left]]s. Called just Northwestern Highway, M-10 runs through suburban residential areas of Southfield. At the intersection with Inkster Road, the highway clips the southwest corner of the city of [[Franklin, Michigan|Franklin]] and enters the northeastern corner of [[Farmington Hills, Michigan|Farmington Hills]]. The roadway is lined with commercial properties while just behind them are residential subdivisions and two golf courses. At the intersection with 14&nbsp;Mile Road, Northwestern Highway crosses into [[West Bloomfield Township, Michigan|West Bloomfield Township]], and {{convert|1/4|mi|km}} further on, the highway ends at Orchard Lake Road.<ref name=MDOT14D/><ref name=google/>

==History==
===Previous designations===
{{infobox road small
|state=MI
|type=M 1919
|route=10
|location=[[Ohio]] state line<U+2013>[[Mackinaw City, Michigan|Mackinaw City]]
|length_mi=
|length_ref=
|formed={{circa|July 1, 1919}}<ref name=MSHD19LP/>
|deleted=November 11, 1926<ref name=USH/>
}}
In 1919, the state numbered its highways for the first time.<ref name=press-1919-09-20>{{cite news |title=Michigan May Do Well Following Wisconsin's Road Marking System |work= [[The Grand Rapids Press]] |date= September 20, 1919 |page=10 |oclc= 9975013}}</ref> In the initial allocation of numbers, M-10 was assigned to a highway that started at the Ohio state line south of [[Monroe, Michigan|Monroe]], ran northeasterly along Telegraph Road into [[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]] and turned easterly into [[Detroit]]. From there, the highway turned north along Woodward Avenue through [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]] and Dixie Highway through [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]] and [[Saginaw, Michigan|Saginaw]] to [[Bay City, Michigan|Bay City]]. Then M-10 ran along the [[Saginaw Bay]] to [[Standish, Michigan|Standish]] and turned to follow the [[Lake Huron]] shoreline, with some substantial deviations inland. The highway generally followed the lakeshore as far north as [[Alpena, Michigan|Alpena]] and [[Rogers City, Michigan|Rogers City]], and from there, M-10 ran due west through [[Onaway, Michigan|Onaway]] before turning north into [[Cheboygan, Michigan|Cheboygan]]. The last section of M-10 followed the Lake Huron shoreline to [[Mackinaw City, Michigan|Mackinaw City]], where it terminated.<ref name=MSHD19LP>{{cite MDOT map |date= 1919-07-01L |link= yes}}</ref> This designation lasted until November 11, 1926, when the [[United States Numbered Highway System]] was created.<ref name=mcnichol>{{cite book |last= McNichol |first= Dan |year= 2006 |title= The Roads that Built America |location= New York |publisher= Sterling |isbn= 1-4027-3468-9 |page= 74}}</ref> In Michigan's initial allocation of highways, four new designations replaced M-10: [[U.S. Route 24 in Michigan|US&nbsp;24]] from the state line north to Dearborn, [[U.S. Route 112|US&nbsp;112]] between Dearborn and Detroit, [[U.S. Route 10 in Michigan|US&nbsp;10]] from Detroit to Saginaw, and [[U.S. Route 23 in Michigan|US&nbsp;23]]  from Saginaw to Mackinaw City.<ref name="USH">{{cite map |author1= [[Bureau of Public Roads]] |author2= [[American Association of State Highway Officials]] |date= November 11, 1926 |title= United States System of Highways Adopted for Uniform Marking by the American Association of State Highway Officials |url= http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth298433/m1/1/zoom/ |scale= 1:7,000,000 |location= Washington, DC |publisher= [[U.S. Geological Survey]] |oclc= 32889555 |access-date= November 7, 2013 |via= University of North Texas Libraries |last-author-amp= yes}}</ref> At the time, no M-10 designation was reassigned to any other roads.<ref name=MSHD26-12>{{cite MDOT map |date= 1926-12-01}}</ref>

{{infobox road small
|state=MI
|type=M 1926
