The second iteration of M-10 was designated in 1929 on a much shorter segment of the original M-10 through the Flint area, serving as a business connection for the city as the through route, US&nbsp;10, bypassed it on the east.<ref name=MSHD29-05>{{cite MDOT map |date= 1929-05-01}}</ref><ref name=MSHD30-01>{{cite MDOT map |date= 1930-01-01 |c-link= yes}}</ref> It was later redesignated as [[U.S. Route 10 Business (Flint, Michigan)|Business US 10]] (Bus. US&nbsp;10) in 1941,<ref name=MSHD41-03>{{cite MDOT map |date= 1941-03-21 |c-link= yes |section= K12}}</ref><ref name=MSHD41-07>{{cite MDOT map |date= 1941-07-01|section= K12}}</ref> and then as [[M-54 Business (Flint, Michigan)|Bus. M-54]] in 1962<ref name=MSHD62>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1962 |sections= K12<U+2013>L12 }}</ref><ref name=MSHD63>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1963 |sections= K12<U+2013>L12 }}</ref> before being turned back to local control in 1974.<ref name=MDSHT74>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1974 |link= yes |section= K12}}</ref><ref name=MDSHT75>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1975 |section= K12}}</ref>
{{-}}

===Current designation===
During the 1950s, the Lodge Freeway was proposed to run from Detroit as far as the Fenton<U+2013>Clio Expressway (US&nbsp;23) at [[Fenton, Michigan|Fenton]].<ref name="greenwood99">{{cite news |first=Tom |last=Greenwood |title= M-5 'Haggerty Connector' Work to Be Done by 2001 |work= [[The Detroit News]] |date=January 28, 1999}}</ref> The intersection with the [[Edsel Ford Freeway]], next to [[Wayne State University]] was built in 1953 and was the first full freeway-to-freeway interchange built in the United States.<ref name="significant">{{cite web |first= MaryAnn |last= Naber |date= November 1, 2006 |url= http://www.environment.fhwa.dot.gov/histpres/highways_list.asp |title= Final List of Nationally and Exceptionally Significant Features of the Federal Interstate Highway System |publisher= [[Federal Highway Administration]] |accessdate= February 27, 2007}}</ref>  The freeway was dedicated on November 7, 1957,<ref name=dedication>{{cite book |author= John C. Lodge Expressway Dedication Committee |title= John C. Lodge Expressway Dedication Program |location= Detroit |publisher= John C. Lodge Expressway Dedication Committee |year= 1957 |oclc= 34869718}}</ref> and opened without any state trunkline designation between downtown and the Wyoming Curve.<ref name=MSHD58>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1958 |inset= Detroit}}</ref> The section from the Edsel Ford Freeway (now I-94) into downtown Detroit was designated as [[U.S. Route 12 in Michigan|US&nbsp;12]] in the by the middle of 1960.<ref name=MSHD60D>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1960 |inset= Detroit}}</ref>

