The freeway was then redesignated [[Interstate 696 Business (Detroit, Michigan)|Business Spur I-696]] (BS I-696) in 1962,<ref name=MSHD62>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1962 |inset= Detroit}}</ref><ref name=MSHD63>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1963 |inset= Detroit}}</ref>  and the next year the freeway was extended northwesterly along James Couzens Highway and Northwestern Highway into Southfield,<ref name=MSHD63/><ref name=MSHD64>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1964 |inset= Detroit}}</ref> connecting with the completed first phase of [[Interstate 696|I-696]] that opened in 1963-64.<ref name=brown>{{cite news |last= Brown |first= Warren |date= February 4, 1990 |title= Home of the American Auto Finds Reuther Freeway a Mixed Blessing |work= [[The Washington Post]] |page= H2 |issn= 0740-5421 |url= http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72563420.html?dids=72563420:72563420&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+04%2C+1990&author=Warren+Brown&pub=The+Washington+Post+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Home+of+the+American+Auto+Finds+Reuther+Freeway+a+Mixed+Blessing |accessdate= July 13, 2012 |subscription= yes}}</ref> That designation remained until 1970 when US&nbsp;10 was shifted off Woodward Avenue to follow the Lodge Freeway between downtown Detroit and Telegraph Road, replacing the BS I-696 designation.<ref name=MDSH70>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1970 |link= yes. |sections= A6<U+2013>E9 |inset= Detroit }}</ref><ref name=MDSH71>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1971 |sections=A6<U+2013>E9 |inset= Detroit }}</ref>

{{infobox road small
|state=MI
|type=M
|route=4
|location=[[Farmington Hills, Michigan|Farmington Hills]]<U+2013>[[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]]
|formed=1979<ref name=MDSHT79/><ref name=MDOT80/>
|deleted=1986<ref name=MDOT86/><ref name=MDOT87/>
|length_mi= 4.687
|length_ref=<ref name=PRFA/>
}}
An extension to the Northwestern Highway was again proposed in 1966 to connect with the proposed [[Interstate 275 (Michigan)|I-275]] extension.<ref>{{cite report |author= Route Location Division |year= 1966 |title= Proposed Northwestern Highway from Telegraph Road to I-275 Extension, Oakland County, Control Section 63082, Length 9.7 Miles |location= Lansing |publisher= Michigan Department of State Highways |oclc= 15364441}}</ref> The I-275 project was then cancelled in 1977.<ref name="stuart">{{cite news |first= Reginald A. |last= Stuart |title= Michigan Drops $69-Million Road |work= [[The New York Times]] |date= January 27, 1977 |page= 18 |issn= 0362-4331}}</ref> The section of Northwestern Highway under state control between the [[West Bloomfield Township, Michigan|West Bloomfield Township]]<U+2013>[[Farmington Hills, Michigan|Farmington Hills]] border into Southfield was numbered M-4 in 1979.<ref name=MDSHT79>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1979 |inset= Detroit |sections= C5<U+2013>C6}}</ref><ref name=MDOT80>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1980 |inset= Detroit |sections= C2<U+2013>C3}}</ref>

The [[Michigan Department of Transportation]] (MDOT) petitioned the [[American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials]] in the mid-1980s to truncate US&nbsp;10 to [[Bay City, Michigan|Bay City]]. The request was approved on October 11, 1985,<ref name=AASHTO85A>{{AASHTO minutes |year= 1985A |link= yes |v-link= yes}}</ref> and the signage was changed the next year. After the change, the Lodge Freeway was redesignated M-10. The non-freeway Northwestern Highway, until then designated M-4, was also renumbered as M-10. The southernmost portion of the Lodge Freeway was also initially redesignated as a portion of [[Interstate 375 Business (Detroit, Michigan)|BS I-375]] from I-75 south.<ref name=MDOT86>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1986 |inset= Detroit |sections= C5<U+2013>E8}}</ref><ref name=MDOT87>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1987 |inset= Detroit |sections= C5<U+2013>E8}}</ref> By the next year however, the southern end of M-10 was moved to the corner of Jefferson and Randolph, placing all of the Lodge Freeway as part of M-10.<ref name=MDOT87/><ref name=MDOT88>{{cite MDOT map |year= 1988 |inset= Detroit |sections= C5<U+2013>E8}}</ref>

From 2006 to 2007, the Lodge underwent major reconstruction to ease traffic congestion in the metro area, temporarily closing down much of the freeway.<ref>{{cite web |author= Staff |url= http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9621_11008_44528---,00.html |title= Dodge the Lodge II |publisher= Michigan Department of Transportation |date= January 23, 2007 |accessdate=March 21, 2007 |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070312025350/http://www.michigan.gov/mdot/0,1607,7-151-9621_11008_44528---,00.html |archivedate= March 12, 2007}}</ref> The $133&nbsp;million project (equivalent to ${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US-NGDPPC|133000000|2007|r=0}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-NGDPPC}}{{Inflation-fn|US-NGDPPC|lastauthoramp=yes}}) included concrete pavement reconstruction and rehabilitation, new barrier walls, repairs or replacements to 50 bridges, upgrades to 22 ramps, utility upgrades, and replacement of freeway signs between Lahser Road in Southfield and Jefferson Avenue in Detroit.<ref>{{cite news |first= Aram |last= Kalousdian |url= http://www.acppubs.com/article/CA6451824.html |title= Massive Lodge Project Proceeds |work= Michigan Contractor and Builder |via= Associated Construction Publications |date= June 17, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928010312/http://www.acppubs.com/article/CA6451824.html |archive-date= September 28, 2007}}</ref>

==Memorial highway names==
{{Multiple image
|align= right
|direction= horizontal
|image1= James Couzens.jpg
|width1=144
|alt1= Portrait of James J. Couzens
|image2= John C Lodge Detroit.jpg
|width2=156
|alt2= Portrait of John C. Lodge
|footer= James J. Couzens (left) and John C. Lodge (right) have been namesakes for parts of M-10 in Detroit
}}

Starting in 1924, officials in southeastern Michigan proposed building a highway from Detroit to run northwesterly across the state to [[Ludington, Michigan|Ludington]], bisecting the angle created by [[Woodward Avenue|Woodward]] and [[Grand River Avenue|Grand River]] avenues. This roadway was named Northwestern Highway when it was built in 1929 to an endpoint at 14&nbsp;Mile Road. Further construction on Northwestern Highway was halted by the [[Great Depression]].<ref name=barnett>{{cite book |last= Barnett |first= LeRoy |year= 2004 |title= A Drive Down Memory Lane: The Named State and Federal Highways of Michigan |location= Allegan Forest, MI |publisher= Priscilla Press |pages= 116<U+2013>17, 121 |isbn= 1-886167-24-9}}</ref>

The freeway segment northwest of Wyoming Avenue to the county line was previously known as James Couzens Highway after the street it replaced. That street was named after the death of [[James J. Couzens]]. Couzens was a former Commissioner of Detroit's [[Department of Street Railways]] from 1913 through 1915, after which he served as Police Commissioner from 1916 until 1918. He was [[Mayor of Detroit]] from 1919 until 1922 and [[United States congressional delegations from Michigan|United States Senator from Michigan]] from 1922 until his death on October 22, 1936. During his years of public service, he is said not to have accepted a salary, giving it all to charity. After his death, Detroit renamed its section of Northwestern Highway after Couzens.<ref name=barnett/>

[[John C. Lodge]] was a a member of the constitutional convention which drafted the Michigan Constitution of 1908, a former member of the [[Michigan Legislature]] and Detroit alderman and councilman. He later served as Mayor of Detroit in 1918<U+2013>1919 before returned to the City Common Council from 1932 to 1947. He was then elected to the Wayne County Board of Supervisors from 1948 until 1950. In total, he held elective office longer than anyone in city history. He died on February 6, 1950, and the future Lodge Freeway was named in his honor on January 20, 1953.<ref name=barnett/> The entire freeway, including segments previously named for James Couzens and the Northwestern Highway was named the John C. Lodge Freeway in 1987, although the service drives retained their original names.<ref>{{cite web |first= Caitlin |last= Brennecke |date= n.d. |title= John C. Lodge Freeway |url= http://detroithistorical.org/learn/encyclopedia-of-detroit/john-c-lodge-freeway |work= Encyclopedia of Detroit |access-date= April 12, 2015}}</ref>

